"Pertoldi C., Bach L.A.","Evolutionary aspects of climate-induced changes and the need for multidisciplinarity",2007,"Journal of Thermal Biology","32","3",,"118","124",,,10.1016/j.jtherbio.2007.01.011,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33847338591&partnerID=40&md5=966b6f2fee70f2b3200e850ffa705a76","Department of Ecology and Genetics, University of Aarhus, Building 540, Ny Munkegade, DK-8000 Aarhus C, Denmark; Department of Wildlife Ecology and Biodiversity, National Environmental Research, Institute, Kalø Grenåvej 14, DK-8410 Rønde, Denmark; Department of Theoretical Ecology, Lund University, Ecology Building Sölvegatan, SE-223 62 Lund, Sweden","Pertoldi, C., Department of Ecology and Genetics, University of Aarhus, Building 540, Ny Munkegade, DK-8000 Aarhus C, Denmark, Department of Wildlife Ecology and Biodiversity, National Environmental Research, Institute, Kalø Grenåvej 14, DK-8410 Rønde, Denmark; Bach, L.A., Department of Theoretical Ecology, Lund University, Ecology Building Sölvegatan, SE-223 62 Lund, Sweden","An integrated view on the possible effects of global climate change is provided while taking into account that not only the rising average temperature is likely to impact natural populations but also that increased variation around the mean and higher frequency of extreme events will be important. We propose that complex genetic effects in concert with demographic patterns may affect how focal populations react to the environmental challenge in an adaptive way (if they can). In order to aim for an inclusive picture of the ongoing environmental change we argue for a synthesis of knowledge from a range of 'classical' disciplines such as quantitative genetics, conservation genetics and population ecology. A hereto little exposed concern is the importance of the increase in amplitude of environmental fluctuations and how the corresponding evolutionary and ecological reactions are expected to occur. Due to the complex interactions between the ecological and genetic mechanisms in the response to climate-induced impacts interdisciplinary approaches are the most promising path in seeking knowledge about the present and future changes in the biosphere. © 2007 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Adaptive potential; Climate change; Environmental variability; Fluctuating population size; Genetic diversity","article; biodiversity; biosphere; climate change; conservation genetics; demography; ecology; environmental temperature; evolution; global climate; quantitative genetics",,,,,,"Altieri, M.A., The ecological role of biodiversity in agroecosystems (1999) Agric. Ecosyst. Environ., 74, pp. 19-31; Andersen, H.D., Pertoldi, C., Scali, V., Loeschcke, V., Intraspecific hybridisation, developmental stability and fitness in Drosophila mercatorum (2002) Evol. Ecol. Res., 4, pp. 603-621; Bach, L.A., Thomsen, R., Pertoldi, C., Loeschcke, V., Kin competition and the evolution of dispersal in an individual-based model (2006) Ecol. Model., 192 (3-4), pp. 658-666; Barbraud, C., Weimerskirch, H., Climate and density shape population dynamics of a marine top predator (2003) Proc. R. Soc. B, 270, pp. 2111-2116; Bijlsma, R., Bundgaard, J., Boerema, A.C., Does inbreeding affect the extinction risk of small populations?: predictions from Drosophila (2000) J. Evol. Biol., 13, pp. 502-514; Bradshaw, W.E., Holzapfel, C.M., Genetic shift in photoperiodic response correlated with global warming (2001) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA, 98, pp. 14509-14511; Bulmer, M.G., The effect of selection on genetic variability (1971) Am. Nat., 105, p. 201; Bürger, R., Lynch, M., Evolution and extinction in a changing environment: a quantitative-genetic analysis (1995) Evolution, 49, pp. 151-163; Caballero, A., Developments in the prediction of effective population size (1994) Heredity, 73, pp. 657-679; Caprio, M.A., Tabashnik, B.E., Gene flow accelerates local adaptation among finite populations: simulating the evolution of insecticide resistance (1